servings: 2
source: https://www.hellofresh.co.uk/recipes/peri-peri-spiced-chorizo-pilaf-66b22e2f6e2625457a71ce96
---

Halve, peel and thinly slice the @onion{1}(halved and thinly sliced).

Heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in a deep #saucepan{} (with a #tight-fitting lid{}) on
medium heat.

Once hot, add half the @butter{15%g}(divided) and allow to melt. Add the onion, season
with @salt{} and @pepper{} and fry, stirring occasionally, until golden and softened,
~{10-12%minutes}.

Meanwhile, peel and grate the @garlic{2%cloves}(peeled and grated).

Once the onions have softened, add the @diced chorizo{90%g} and fry until it starts to
brown, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Next, add the garlic, @peri peri seasoning{2%sachets} and @sugar{1/2%tsp}, stir-fry for
~{30%seconds}, until fragrant.

Stir in the @cider vinegar{15%ml} and allow it to evaporate, ~{1%minute}.

Stir the @basmati rice{150%g} into the pan until coated, ~{1%minute}.

Next, stir in the @water for the rice{300%ml}(see pantry for amount) and
@chicken stock paste{15%g}. Bring to the boil.

Once boiling, turn the heat down to medium and cover with the #lid{}.

Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat (still covered) and
leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} (the rice will continue to cook in its own
steam).

Meanwhile, quarter the @lemon{1}(quartered).

Once ready, stir the @peas{120%g}, @red pepper chilli jelly{25%g} and a good squeeze of
lemon juice into the rice along with the remaining butter.

Pop the lid back on and allow to stand for ~{1-2%minutes}.

Taste and season with salt, pepper and lemon juice if you feel it needs it. Add a splash
of water if it's a little dry.

Share the peri peri spiced chorizo pilaf between your #bowls{}.

Finish with a drizzle of @soured cream{75%g} and any remaining lemon wedges alongside
for squeezing over.

Enjoy!